Feature: FES second-swarm bring-up — live/recorded acceptance (Windows launch, Telegram separation)

# BL-439 (epic BL-435, slice 4). This .feature.draft preserves the two acceptance behaviours that are
# INHERENTLY LIVE and therefore NOT executable in-process — the runner throws on any scenario lacking a
# handler, and no in-process handler can stand up a real second swarm or observe live Telegram delivery.
# They are verified by hand per the ticket's E2E QA PROCEDURE. The two testable-seam behaviours (own creds
# resolution, fleet status enumeration) are materialized as executable scenarios in the sibling
# BL-439-fes-second-swarm-bringup.feature.
#
# AMENDED 2026-07-16 (human decision): FES runs as a mono-rotate pack (BL-448), NOT a 2-pack — the 15GB
# host OOM-crashed holding one full swarm, so FES adopts the lightest config: one resident pipeline agent
# rotating through all roles. Launched from the Windows-side swarmforge checkout (target on /mnt/c, where
# Linux-side tmux sockets are unreliable), with its own bot+group (@fes_swarm_bot).

Background:
  Given the primary swarm is running with its own bot and group

# BL-439 fes-second-swarm-bringup-01  (LIVE / recorded QA procedure — not executable)
Scenario: Following the runbook stands up the FES swarm as a mono-rotate pack with its own swarm_name
  When the FES bring-up runbook is followed
  Then a second swarm named "fes" runs as a mono-rotate pack
  And it is launched from the Windows-side checkout against the /mnt/c target

# BL-439 fes-second-swarm-bringup-03  (LIVE / recorded QA procedure — not executable)
Scenario: Neither swarm's inbound is consumed by the other
  Given both the primary and FES swarms are polling their own bots
  When a message is sent to the primary's bot
  Then the FES swarm does not consume it
  And when a message is sent to the FES bot the primary swarm does not consume it
